f teaching and learning, and ways of knowing in education. The book's contributors—Chicana/Latina feminist scholars—reinterpret the field of education as inter- and transdisciplinary and connected to ethnic, racial, and womanist scholarship. They examine mujer- (women-) centered definitions of pedagogy and epistemology rooted in Chicana/Latina theories and visions of life, family, community, and world. Armed with the tools of Chicana/Latina feminist thought, the contributors link cultural studies theories to critical/feminist pedagogies by re-envisioning the sites of pedagogy to include women's brown bodies and their agency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCritical pedagogyzUnited States. 0aFeminist theoryzUnited States. 0aHispanic American womenxEducation. 0aWomen in educationzUnited States. 4aEducation : Education. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAyala, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBañuelos, L. Esthela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBentley, Courtney C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernal, Dolores Delgado, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurciaga, Rebeca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarrillo, Rosario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz, Cindy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelgado Bernal, Dolores, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDicochea, Perlita R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDixon, Iris R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElenes, C. Alejandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb